Recommender Systems

A recommender system relies on input from many users to predict what products other users will like. Good recommendations can be central to the profitability of companies like Amazon and Netflix. As a first example, suppose that your goal is to predict how much a user will like a movie they have not yet watched, assuming that all ratings are on the 0-5 scale.

  • Call n(u) the number of users
  • Call n(m) the number of movies
  • Set r(i, j) = 1 whenever user j has rated movie i (0 or NA otherwise)
  • Set y(i, j) as the rating given by user j for movie i, created only in cases where r(i, j)=1
  • Suppose you have calculated values for features x0 (bias, always 1), x1, and x2 for each movie; x1 might be degree of romance and x2 might be degree of violence
  • Define theta(j) as the prediction vector for user j - how do x0, x1, and x2 combine to make movies good/bad for user j?

The goal is then to learn theta(j) for every user, with a goal of minimizing the prediction costs. Specifically:

  • J = (1 / (2 * m(j) ) * sum-over-r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) )^2 ] + ( lambda / (2 * m(j) ) * sum( theta^2 ), excluding theta0 from the regularization term
  • Since m(j) is a constant for the specific user, can multiply by m(j)
  • So, J = 0.5 * sum-over-r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) )^2 ] + ( 0.5 * lambda ) * sum( theta^2 ), excluding theta0 from the regularization term

And then for all users, we would have:

  • J(theta(1), theta(2), . . . , theta(n(u)) = { 0.5 * sum-over-j-of [ sum-over-r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) )^2 ] ] } + 0.5 * lambda * sum-over-j-of [ sum-over-k=1+ of [ theta(k)(j)^2 ] ]
  • Gradient Descent: theta(k)(j) = theta(k)(j) - alpha * { sum-over-r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) ) * x(k)(i) ] + lambda * thata(j)(k) }, noting that lambda should never be applied if k=0

Of course, the challenge is that this algorithm requires creating features for every movie. This could be cumbersome and inaccurate. On the one hand, we could ask each person to declare their own theta vector and then use that to calculate the features for each movie (using cost minimization). But, could we instead ask the algorithm to calculate both the features and theta vector simultaneously?

Collaborative Filtering (Background)

Collaborative filtering is the solution. Each user gives ratings for movies that they have watched, and the algorithm simultaneously solves for features by movie and thetas by user in a manner that minimizes costs. The name comes from the fact that a large group of people are pooling their inputs in a manner that helps make better (lower cost/error) recommendations for everyone.

  • J = 0.5 * sum-over-(I,j):r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) )^2 ] + ( 0.5 * lambda ) * sum( x(k)(i)^2 ) + ( 0.5 * lambda ) * sum( theta^2 )
  • There is no longer any need for a bias unit - the algorithm can create a bias unit if it likes
  • Each x is an n-dimensional vector, and each theta is an n-dimensional vector; the n features are picked by the model
  • Begin by initializing every theta and feature to a small random number (important for breaking symmetry)
  • x(k)(i) = x(k)(i) - alpha * { sum-over-j:r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) ) * theta(k)(j) ] + lambda * x(k)(i) }
  • theta(k)(j) = theta(k)(j) - alpha * { sum-over-i:r(I,j)=1-of [ ( t(theta(j)) * x(i) - y(I, j) ) * x(k)(i) ] + lambda * theta(k)(j) }
  • After convergence, use t(theta) * x to predict how a user will rate a movie they have not yet seen

While the final features will not have meaning per se, they can be used to group similar movies and similar users by finding small euclidean distances between movie features and/or user thetas

Next an algorithm is created to calculate the cost given the relevant thetas and features:

cofiCost <- function(vecMatrix, mtxY, mtxR, nUser, nMovie, nFeature, lambda) {
    
    # Roll vecMatrix back to feature matrix and theta matrix
    keyCut <- nMovie * nFeature
    vecX <- vecMatrix[1:keyCut]
    vecTheta <- vecMatrix[(keyCut+1):length(vecMatrix)]
    useX <- matrix(data=vecX, nrow=nMovie, ncol=nFeature, byrow=FALSE)
    useTheta <- matrix(data=vecTheta, nrow=nUser, ncol=nFeature, byrow=FALSE)
    
    # Calculate cost
    movJ <- 0.5 * sum( ( (useX %*% t(useTheta) - mtxY)^2)[mtxR==1] )
    movJ <- movJ + 0.5 * lambda * ( sum(useX^2) + sum(useTheta^2) )
    
    return(movJ)
}

So, provided that we have the proper inputs, we can calculate the associated costs. The next step is to find the gradients and optimize the parameters.

Collaborative Filtering (Example Solving for Input Matrices)

The process of simultaneously solving for theta and features is an example of low rank matrix factorization. The rank of an mxn matrix is typically the smaller of m or n, defining the degree of linear independence that exists in the matrix. However, when certain rows and/or columns are linear combinations of each other, the matrix is no longer considered to be full rank. Instead, the matrix is considered to be rank deficient and to have rank equal to the smaller of # linearly independent columns/rows. Fortunately, gradient descent works fine even in a rank-deficient environment:

cofiGrad <- function(vecMatrix, mtxY, mtxR, nUser, nMovie, nFeature, lambda) {
    
    # Roll vecMatrix back to feature matrix and theta matrix
    keyCut <- nMovie * nFeature
    vecX <- vecMatrix[1:keyCut]
    vecTheta <- vecMatrix[(keyCut+1):length(vecMatrix)]
    useX <- matrix(data=vecX, nrow=nMovie, ncol=nFeature, byrow=FALSE)
    useTheta <- matrix(data=vecTheta, nrow=nUser, ncol=nFeature, byrow=FALSE)
    
    # Calculate gradients
    gradX <- ((useX %*% t(useTheta) - mtxY) * mtxR) %*% useTheta + (lambda * useX)
    gradTheta <- t((useX %*% t(useTheta) - mtxY) * mtxR) %*% useX + (lambda * useTheta)
    
    return(c(as.vector(gradX), as.vector(gradTheta)))
    
}

Then, we can initialize theta and X as small random numbers (break the symmetry), normalize the movie ratings, and call optim to find the solution:

The outcomes are intriguing and show that optim() is the primary time-sink:

  • 10 runs of the cost function take ~0.6 seconds
  • 10 runs of the gradient function take ~1.1 seconds
  • Total cost after 10 runs of BFGS is ~160k, roughly double the ~75k seen above at 50 iterations
  • 43 runs of cost and 10 runs of gradient made by way of BFGS in optim() take ~150 seconds
  • Extrapolating, the raw functions should take 4.3 * 0.6 + 1.1 = ~3.5 seconds

So, it appears that the optim() function using BFGS is taking 30x-40x longer than calls to the underlying functions would suggest. One potential reason is that BFGS is storing a matrix - see below for some comments from Details under ?optim:

  • Method BFGS is a quasi-Newton method (also known as a variable metric algorithm), specifically that published simultaneously in 1970 by Broyden, Fletcher, Goldfarb and Shanno. This uses function values and gradients to build up a picture of the surface to be optimized.
  • Method CG is a conjugate gradients method based on that by Fletcher and Reeves (1964) (but with the option of Polak-Ribiere or Beale-Sorenson updates). Conjugate gradient methods will generally be more fragile than the BFGS method, but as they do not store a matrix they may be successful in much larger optimization problems.

As such, it would be interesting to test the performance using the conjugate gradients method, particularly since that will be a closer match to what is used in the Octave/MATLAB examples:

The time consumed by the additional runs is roughly proportional to the increased number of iterations, suggesting that CG is a good method for this particular problem. Further, there is almost no improvement in the overall cost when moving from 10 iterations CG -> 250 iterations CG, which suggests that a nice process might involve a smaller number of iterations but with more robust tuning of the optimal lambda parameter:

cofiValues <- c(movListBFGS010$value, movList$value, movListCG010$value, 
                movListCG050$value, movListCG250$value 
                )

plot(cofiValues/1000, xaxt="n", ylab="Cost in 000s (lambda=10)", main="Cost by Algorithm", 
     pch=19, col="blue", cex=2, xlab="", ylim=c(0, 50 * ceiling(max(cofiValues)/50000) )
     )
axis(1, at=1:5, labels=c("BFGS 10 iter", "BFGS 50 iter", "CG 10 iter", "CG 50 iter", "CG 250 iter"))

The moral seems clear - for this type of problem, use method=CG for optimization!

It would also be interesting to understand whether method=CG could help with the neural network tuned previously. The results are again interesting and show the enormous timing advantage for CG over BFGS. For example:

  • 10 runs of nnCost takes ~1 seconds
  • 10 runs of nnGradient takes ~1.6 seconds
  • Running optim() using BFGS for 150 iterations takes ~240 seconds, while making 151 calls to nnCost and 150 calls to nnGradient; these should only take ~40 seconds, so optim() is taking ~6x as long as expected
  • Running optim() using CG for 10 iterations takes ~3.5 seconds, while making 21 calls to nnCost and 11 calls to nnGradient; these should take ~4 seconds, suggesting very little inefficiency
  • Running optim() using CG for 50 iterations takes ~18 seconds, while making 106 calls to nnCost and 51 calls to nnGradient; these should take ~19 seconds, suggesting very little inefficiency
  • Running optim() using CG for 150 iterations takes ~55 seconds, while making 322 calls to nnCost and 151 calls to nnGradient; these should take ~55 seconds, suggesting very little inefficiency
  • Running optim() using CG for 300 iterations takes ~120 seconds, while making 643 calls to nnCost and 301 calls to nnGradient; these should take ~115 seconds, suggesting very little inefficiency

Additionally, the results are again plotted to see the estimated cost rates:

nnCostValues <- c(nnListBFGS150$value, nnListCG010$value, nnListCG050$value, 
                  nnListCG150$value, nnListCG300$value
                  )

     )
axis(1, at=1:5, labels=c("BFGS 150 iter", "CG 10 iter", "CG 50 iter", "CG 150 iter", "CG 300 iter"))

Interestingly, though, in this case CG is not converging to as good solution as had been observed in the BFGS modeling. So, the algorithm may be faster but less accurate for this specific case.

Gradient Descent with Large Datasets

With much more data available, it is possible to build low bias models that are also low variance. It is again he who has the best data that wins. But, working with the very largest data requires different techniques:

  • Suppose that you have 100 million observations (m=100 million)
  • This would mean that you need to sum across 100 million observations to find the gradient
  • A good idea is to first look at the learning curves for a smaller sample - if it shows high variance, more data may help, but if it shows high bias then more data will likely not help

If the full 100 million record dataset appears to be useful, then there are techniques for running gradient descent more quickly. One example is stochastic gradient descent:

  • Randomly shuffle the dataset (in case there is some structure)
  • Repeatedly run i=1 to m, and calculate theta(j) = theta(j) - alpha * { ( h(x(i)) - y(i) ) * x(j)(i) }
  • This means theta is being updated every time we see a data point; in fact, sometimes a single pass through the descent gets you to a good point
  • The main downside is that it means there is a meandering path to the global minima, which is never actually hit; however, the descent tends to find a good enough solution

Another example approach is mini-batch, where b=10 is common, and b is very often in the range of 2-100. The mini-batch approach uses b data points at once and alpha/b, meaning that 1) it can be vectorized, but 2) it requires an additional parameter. If the code for mini-batch is not vectorized, then there is no real gain.

Plotting cost curves is recommended with stochastic gradient descent or mini-batch gradient descent. Basically, plot the cost after every 1,000 iterations and see how well it is converging. If the cost is generally growing or oscillating too wildly, that may signal that alpha is too large.

Lets try an example of the mini-batch approach for the neural network problem run above:

# Re-initialize vecPass to the beginning values
vecPass=c(as.vector(bpThetaOne), as.vector(bpThetaTwo))  # Roll together bpThetaOne and bpThetaTwo

# Use a batch size of 50
nBatch <- 50

# What percentage of the data will be passed each time?  
# Need to scale lambda by this while running mini-batch gradients
keyRat <- nBatch / nrow(mtxX)


# Calculate the starting cost (full dataset)
startCost <- nnCost(vecMatrix=vecPass, nInputLayer, nHiddenNodes, nFinalLabels, 
                    X=mtxX, y=mtxY, lambda=1
                    )

# Set vecUse as vecPass and alpha=1 (rather large)
vecUse <- vecPass
alpha <- 1

# Set the number of runs and the timing for plotting the learning curve
nRuns <- 5000
nPerSave <- 1000
nPerSave <- nBatch * ceiling(nPerSave/nBatch)
costSave <- numeric(length=nRuns*nBatch/nPerSave)

startTime <- proc.time()

# Run through 5000 mini-batch descents
# Since the gradients already come back with 1/m, do not divide alpha by nBatch
for (intCtr in 1:nRuns) {
    miniRand <- sample(1:nrow(mtxX), nBatch, replace=FALSE)
    
    # Pass a smaller lambda to nnGradient to not over-penalize large thetas
    vecUse <- vecUse - (alpha) * nnGradient(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer, nHiddenNodes, 
                                            nFinalLabels, X=mtxX[miniRand, ], 
                                            y=mtxY[miniRand, ,drop=FALSE], lambda=1*keyRat
                                            )
    
    # Calculate actual costs based on all data (unscaled lambda)
    if ((intCtr * nBatch) %% nPerSave == 0) {
        costSave[[(intCtr * nBatch) %/% nPerSave]] <- nnCost(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer, 
                                                             nHiddenNodes, nFinalLabels, 
                                                             X=mtxX, y=mtxY, lambda=1
                                                             )
    }
    
}

proc.time() - startTime
##    user  system elapsed 
##   39.77    0.22   40.04
plot(x=0:length(costSave), y=c(startCost, costSave), pch=19, col="blue", cex=0.5,
     ylim=c(0, max(startCost, costSave)), xlab="Sample Number", ylab="Total Cost",
     main="Mini-Batch Descent for Neural Network"
     )
abline(h=0.365, lty=2, lwd=2)

# Assess the optimized accuracies
keyCut <- (nInputLayer + 1) * nHiddenNodes
postBPThetaOne <- matrix(data=vecUse[1:keyCut], nrow=nHiddenNodes, byrow=FALSE)
postBPThetaTwo <- matrix(data=vecUse[(keyCut+1):length(vecUse)], 
                         nrow=nFinalLabels, byrow=FALSE
                         )

predYMini <- forwardPredY(mtxX, postBPThetaOne, postBPThetaTwo)
plot(x=1:length(predYMini), y=predYMini, col = 1 + (mtxY[,1] != predYMini), 
     main="Predictions vs Actual (Mini-Batch)", ylab="Prediction (Red=Wrong)", xlab="Index"

So, the mini-batch (5000 batches of 50, or 50 times through the data in total) asymptotes to roughly the same cost as the BFGS 150 optimization, and is essentially at the asymptote by indices 50-100 (having been through the data 10-20 times in total). Importantly, the mini-batch run takes ~40 seconds to get through the data 50 times, in contrast to the ~20 seconds that optim(method=CG) requires to get through the data 50 times. However, the mini-batch approach has converged nicely well before the end of its 40 seconds, while the CG approach still has a bit more convergence to do by 150 iterations. And, the CG approach is in the range of large thetas, so it is achieving its accuracy in a more risky manner.

Careful selection of alpha and lambda play a large role in the convergence, demonstrating how valuable a hold-out sample for tuning key parameters can be.

Holdout Sample for Mini-Batch

The below code implements a brief hold-out example for mini-batch, exploring the predictive power on data the model has not yet seen:

testMiniBatch <- function(vecUse=vecPass, nInputLayer=nInputLayer, nHiddenNodes=nHiddenNodes, 
                          nFinalLabels=nFinalLabels, trainX, trainY, cvX, cvY,
                          useLambda=1, useAlpha=1, nBatch=50, nRuns=5000, nPerSave=1000) {
    
    # Calculate the starting costs for train and test
    startCostTrain <- nnCost(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer, nHiddenNodes, nFinalLabels, 
                             X=trainX, y=trainY, lambda=useLambda
                             )
    startCostTest <- nnCost(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer, nHiddenNodes, nFinalLabels, 
                            X=cvX, y=cvY, lambda=useLambda
                            )
    
    # Set the number of runs and the timing for plotting the learning curve
    keyRat <- nBatch / nrow(trainX)
    nPerSave <- nBatch * ceiling(nPerSave/nBatch)
    costTrainSave <- numeric(length=nRuns*nBatch/nPerSave)
    costTestSave <- numeric(length=nRuns*nBatch/nPerSave)

    startTime <- proc.time()

    # Run through mini-batch routine for train data only
    # Since gradients already come back with 1/m, do not divide useAlpha by nBatch
    for (intCtr in 1:nRuns) {
        miniRand <- sample(1:nrow(trainX), nBatch, replace=FALSE)
    
        # Pass a smaller lambda to nnGradient to not over-penalize large thetas
        vecUse <- vecUse - (useAlpha) * nnGradient(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer, nHiddenNodes, 
                                                   nFinalLabels, X=trainX[miniRand, ], 
                                                   y=trainY[miniRand, ,drop=FALSE], 
                                                   lambda=useLambda*keyRat
                                            )
    
        # Calculate actual costs based on all data (unscaled lambda)
        if ((intCtr * nBatch) %% nPerSave == 0) {
            costTrainSave[[(intCtr * nBatch) %/% nPerSave]] <- nnCost(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer,
                                                                      nHiddenNodes, nFinalLabels, 
                                                                      X=trainX, y=trainY, lambda=useLambda
                                                                 )
            costTestSave[[(intCtr * nBatch) %/% nPerSave]] <- nnCost(vecMatrix=vecUse, nInputLayer,
                                                                     nHiddenNodes, nFinalLabels, 
                                                                     X=cvX, y=cvY, lambda=useLambda
                                                                 )
        }
    
    }

    print(proc.time() - startTime)
    
    # Plot the learning curves
    plot(x=0:length(costTrainSave), y=c(startCostTrain, costTrainSave), pch=19, col="blue", 
         cex=0.5, ylim=c(0, max(startCostTrain, startCostTest, costTrainSave, costTestSave)), 
         xlab="Sample Number", ylab="Total Cost", 
         main="Mini-Batch Descent for Neural Network"
         )
    points(x=0:length(costTestSave), y=c(startCostTest, costTestSave), pch=19, col="red", cex=0.5)
    legend("topright", legend=c("Train", "Test"), pch=19, cex=2, col=c("blue", "red"))
    
    # Assess optimized accuracies
    keyCut <- (nInputLayer + 1) * nHiddenNodes
    postBPThetaOne <- matrix(data=vecUse[1:keyCut], nrow=nHiddenNodes, byrow=FALSE)
    postBPThetaTwo <- matrix(data=vecUse[(keyCut+1):length(vecUse)], 
                             nrow=nFinalLabels, byrow=FALSE
                             )

    predYTrainMini <- forwardPredY(trainX, postBPThetaOne, postBPThetaTwo)
    predYTestMini <- forwardPredY(cvX, postBPThetaOne, postBPThetaTwo)

    par(mfrow=c(1,2))
    
    plot(x=1:length(predYTrainMini), y=predYTrainMini, col = 1 + (trainY[,1] != predYTrainMini), 
         main="Predictions vs Actual (Train)", ylab="Prediction (Red=Wrong)", xlab="Index"
         )
    
    plot(x=1:length(predYTestMini), y=predYTestMini, col = 1 + (cvY[,1] != predYTestMini), 
         main="Predictions vs Actual (Test)", ylab="Prediction (Red=Wrong)", xlab="Index"
         )
    
    par(mfrow=c(1,1))
    
    print(confusionMatrix(predYTrainMini, trainY[,1]))
    print(confusionMatrix(predYTestMini, cvY[,1]))
    
}

vecPass=c(as.vector(bpThetaOne), as.vector(bpThetaTwo))  # Roll together bpThetaOne and bpThetaTwo

              cvX=mtxX[-idxTrain, ], cvY=mtxY[-idxTrain, ,drop=FALSE],
              useLambda=1, useAlpha=1, nBatch=50, nRuns=2000, nPerSave=1000
              )
